[89.304172, "o", "       The  return  value described above for \u001b[01;31mbrk\u001b[00m() is the behavior provided by the glibc wrapper function for the Linux \u001b[01;31mbrk\u001b[00m()\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;33m\u001b[44m Manual page sbrk(2) line 21 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[00m\u001b[K"]
[89.387468, "i", "\u001bOB"]
[89.388069, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K       system call.  (On most other implementations, the return value from \u001b[01;31mbrk\u001b[00m() is the same; this return value was also spec‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;33m\u001b[44m Manual page sbrk(2) line 22 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[00m\u001b[K"]
[89.469682, "i", "\u001bOB"]
[89.470216, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K       ified in SUSv2.)  However, the actual Linux system call returns the new program break on success.  On failure, the sys‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;33m\u001b[44m Manual page sbrk(2) line 23 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[00m\u001b[K"]
[89.554112, "i", "\u001bOB"]
[89.554762, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K       tem call returns the current break.  The glibc wrapper function does some work (i.e., checks whether the new  break  is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;33m\u001b[44m Manual page sbrk(2) line 24 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[00m\u001b[K"]
[89.638332, "i", "\u001bOB"]
[89.63898, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K       less than \u001b[01;32maddr\u001b[00m) to provide the 0 and -1 return values described above.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;33m\u001b[44m Manual page sbrk(2) line 25 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[00m\u001b[K"]
